        "# Exploratory Data Analysis: Uncovering Insights in Bangalore's Restaurant Scene\n",
        "\n",
        "## 1. Project Overview\n",
        "\n",
        "This notebook presents a comprehensive Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) of the Zomato Bangalore Restaurants dataset. [cite_start]The primary objective is to perform an end-to-end analysis of Bangalore's vibrant and competitive food industry[cite: 2]. [cite_start]By dissecting various factors such as location, cuisine, cost, and customer ratings, this project aims to uncover actionable insights and tell a compelling data story[cite: 38]. The analysis is framed as a market research study to identify key success factors and strategic opportunities for launching a new restaurant venture in the city.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 2. Assignment Objectives\n",
        "\n",
        "The analysis is structured to meet the following objectives, as outlined in the assignment guidelines:\n",
        "\n",
        "* [cite_start]**Understand the Dataset**: Interpret the structure and characteristics of a real-world dataset on the Bangalore restaurant market[cite: 5].\n",
        "* [cite_start]**Perform Data Preparation**: Conduct end-to-end data preparation, including data cleaning, handling missing values, and data transformation[cite: 24, 25].\n",
        "* [cite_start]**Conduct Comprehensive EDA**: Perform a thorough analysis covering distribution, outlier, relation, comparative, and dimension-based analyses[cite: 8].\n",
        "* [cite_start]**Identify Key Metrics**: Define and analyze Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) like average rating and cost to measure restaurant performance[cite: 6].\n",
        "* [cite_start]**Generate Actionable Insights**: Derive and present clear, data-driven insights that could inform a strategic business plan for a stakeholder[cite: 37, 39].\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3. Methodology\n",
        "\n",
        "The project follows the **Cross-Industry Standard Process for Data Mining (CRISP-DM)** framework. The notebook will be structured around the key phases: Business Understanding, Data Understanding, Data Preparation, Analysis (Modeling & Evaluation), and finally, a summary of strategic recommendations (Deployment).\n",
        "\n",
        "[cite_start]The analysis is performed using Python with the pandas library for data manipulation and Matplotlib/Seaborn for data visualization[cite: 9, 41].\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 4. Dataset Description\n",
        "\n",
        "The dataset used for this analysis is the **Zomato Bangalore Restaurants dataset**, a popular and rich dataset containing information on approximately 51,000 restaurants. Key features include:\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Location**: The neighborhood in Bangalore.\n",
        "* **Restaurant Type**: The service model (e.g., Quick Bites, Casual Dining).\n",
        "* **Cuisines**: The types of food served.\n",
        "* **Rate**: The aggregated customer rating out of 5.\n",
        "* **Approximate Cost for Two People**: A proxy for the restaurant's price point.\n",
        "\n",
        "Let's begin by loading the data and starting our analysis."
      ],

              "    <script>\n",
              "      const buttonEl =\n",
              "        document.querySelector('#df-84383350-5fc2-4a0c-829b-3ba7b87ec993 button.colab-df-convert');\n",
              "      buttonEl.style.display =\n",
              "        google.colab.kernel.accessAllowed ? 'block' : 'none';\n",
              "\n",
              "      async function convertToInteractive(key) {\n",
              "        const element = document.querySelector('#df-84383350-5fc2-4a0c-829b-3ba7b87ec993');\n",
              "        const dataTable =\n",
              "          await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
              "                                                    [key], {});\n",
              "        if (!dataTable) return;\n",
              "\n",
              "        const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
              "          '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
              "          + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
              "        element.innerHTML = '';\n",
              "        dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
              "        await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
              "        const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
              "        docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
              "        element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
              "      }\n",
              "    </script>\n",
              "  </div>\n",
              "\n",
              "\n",

              "    }\n",

              "      border-bottom-color: var(--fill-color);\n",
              "    }\n",
              "    90% {\n",
              "      border-color: transparent;\n",
              "      border-bottom-color: var(--fill-color);\n",
              "    }\n",
              "  }\n",
              "</style>\n",
              "\n",
              "      <script>\n",
              "        async function quickchart(key) {\n",
              "          const quickchartButtonEl =\n",
              "            document.querySelector('#' + key + ' button');\n",
              "          quickchartButtonEl.disabled = true;  // To prevent multiple clicks.\n",
              "          quickchartButtonEl.classList.add('colab-df-spinner');\n",
              "          try {\n",
              "            const charts = await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction(\n",
              "                'suggestCharts', [key], {});\n",
              "          } catch (error) {\n",
              "            console.error('Error during call to suggestCharts:', error);\n",
              "          }\n",
              "          quickchartButtonEl.classList.remove('colab-df-spinner');\n",
              "          quickchartButtonEl.classList.add('colab-df-quickchart-complete');\n",
              "        }\n",

        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# Load the dataset\n",
        "df = pd.read_csv('/content/zomato.csv')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Display the first 5 rows to confirm it's loaded correctly\n",
        "print(\"Dataset loaded successfully. Here are the first 5 rows:\")\n",
        "df.head()"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Let's see the unique values in the 'rate' column before cleaning\n",
        "print(\"Unique values in 'rate' column BEFORE cleaning:\")\n",
        "print(df['rate'].unique())\n",
        "print(\"-\" * 30)\n",
        "\n",
        "# 1. Define a function to clean the 'rate' column\n",
        "def clean_rate(rate):\n",
        "    if isinstance(rate, str):\n",
        "        # Takes the part before '/5' and removes any extra spaces\n",
        "        rate = rate.split('/')[0].strip()\n",
        "        # Returns a null value for 'NEW' and '-'\n",
        "        if rate == 'NEW' or rate == '-':\n",
        "            return np.nan\n",
        "        else:\n",
        "            return float(rate)\n",
        "    # Returns null for any non-string values (like existing NaNs)\n",
        "    return np.nan\n",
        "\n",
        "# 2. Apply the function to the 'rate' column\n",
        "df['rate'] = df['rate'].apply(clean_rate)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Let's check the data type and a sample of values AFTER cleaning\n",
        "print(\"\\nData type of 'rate' column now:\")\n",
        "print(df['rate'].dtype)\n",
        "print(\"\\nSample of 'rate' values after cleaning:\")\n",
        "print(df['rate'].head())"
      ],

      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# See the unique values before cleaning\n",
        "print(\"Unique values in 'approx_cost(for two people)' BEFORE cleaning:\")\n",
        "print(df['approx_cost(for two people)'].unique()[:10]) # Showing first 10 for brevity\n",
        "print(\"-\" * 30)\n",
        "\n",
        "# 1. Define a function to clean the cost column\n",
        "def clean_cost(cost):\n",
        "    if isinstance(cost, str):\n",
        "        # Remove commas and convert to a number (float)\n",
        "        return float(cost.replace(',', ''))\n",
        "    return np.nan\n",
        "\n",
        "# 2. Apply the function\n",
        "df['approx_cost(for two people)'] = df['approx_cost(for two people)'].apply(clean_cost)\n",
        "\n",
        "# 3. Rename the column for easier access\n",
        "df.rename(columns={'approx_cost(for two people)': 'cost_for_two'}, inplace=True)\n",
        "\n",
        "# 4. Check the result\n",
        "print(\"\\nData type of 'cost_for_two' column now:\")\n",
        "print(df['cost_for_two'].dtype)\n",

      "source": [
        "Insights from Outlier Analysis 🔍\n",
        "1. Restaurant Ratings: A Low Tolerance for Poor Quality\n",
        "Observation: The box plot for ratings shows a number of outliers on the low end (ratings below 2.5), but none on the high end. The main cluster of restaurants performs reliably, with the median rating being quite high.\n",
        "\n",
        "Significance: These low-rated outliers represent restaurants that have significantly failed to meet customer expectations. The market punishes poor quality severely, so maintaining high standards in food, service, and hygiene will be non-negotiable.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. Cost for Two: A Market with Two Tiers\n",
        "Observation: The cost plot shows a large number of outliers, all on the high end. The \"box\" is tightly packed at the lower end (under ~₹800), which represents the mainstream, budget-friendly market. The outliers are the premium and fine-dining establishments, costing anywhere from ~₹1,500 to ₹6,000.\n",
        "\n",
        "Significance: This confirms the existence of a two-tiered market. While the vast majority of competition is in the value segment, there is a distinct, albeit smaller, luxury segment."

        "Relation Analysis - explore the relationship between variables.\n",
        "\n",
        "Does a higher cost lead to a higher rating?"

        "# Set the plot size\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create a regression plot\n",
        "sns.regplot(x='cost_for_two', y='rate', data=df,\n",
        "            scatter_kws={'alpha':0.3, 's':20},  # Makes points semi-transparent and smaller\n",
        "            line_kws={'color':'red'})          # Makes the regression line red\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.title('Relationship Between Cost and Rating')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('Approximate Cost for Two People (in INR)')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Rating (out of 5.0)')\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],

      "source": [
        "Insights from Relation Analysis 🔗\n",
        "Observation: The red trendline clearly shows a weak positive correlation. This means that, in general, as the cost for two people increases, the average rating also tends to increase slightly. However, the data points are very widely scattered, forming a dense cloud.\n",
        "\n",
        "Significance & Insight for NutriGreens: This is a crucial finding. While more expensive restaurants have a tendency to be rated higher, the relationship is not strong at all. At almost every price point below ₹1,500, you can find restaurants spanning the entire spectrum of ratings—from terrible to excellent.\n",
        "\n",
        "The Key Takeaway: You don't have to be expensive to be highly rated. This is fantastic news for a QSR startups. It proves that customers in Bangalore are willing to give high ratings to affordable restaurants as long as the quality is good. The market values quality and experience over price alone. Your focus should be on delivering an excellent product at a competitive price, rather than assuming a higher price will automatically lead to better perception."
      ],

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Comparative Analysis - slicing the data by categories to compare performance.\n",
        "\n",
        "Which type of restaurant performs best in Bangalore?"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "si_Or8Ndn8K3"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Group by restaurant type and calculate mean rating and count\n",
        "rest_type_analysis = df.groupby('rest_type')['rate'].agg(['mean', 'count'])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Filter for restaurant types with a significant number of entries (more than 50)\n",
        "rest_type_analysis = rest_type_analysis[rest_type_analysis['count'] > 50]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Sort the results by mean rating in descending order\n",
        "rest_type_analysis = rest_type_analysis.sort_values(by='mean', ascending=False)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot the results\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\n",
        "sns.barplot(x=rest_type_analysis['mean'], y=rest_type_analysis.index, palette='viridis')\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.title('Average Rating by Restaurant Type')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('Average Rating (out of 5.0)')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Restaurant Type')\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 805
        },

        "outputId": "f817bce8-3676-41d7-acd1-f8996f0c00d4"

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Insights from Comparative Analysis 🏆\n",
        "Observation: The highest-rated categories are often experience-focused venues like \"Pubs,\" \"Microbreweries,\" and \"Casual Dining.\" The 'Quick Bites' (QSR) model, while very common, tends to fall in the solid mid-range of average ratings (typically 3.4 - 3.7).\n",
        "\n",
        "Insight: This tells us that while the QSR model is perfectly viable, it's not the model that customers rate the highest. Customers tend to give top ratings for the overall experience (ambiance, service, food quality). Simply being fast and convenient won't be enough; you'll need to excel in food quality, brand identity, and customer service to compete with the top performers.\n",
        "\n",
        "Data Note: We can see that many categories are combined (e.g., \"Cafe, Bakery\"). This suggests the rest_type column could be cleaned further in a more advanced analysis to isolate the impact of each individual type."

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Dimension Analysis - The goal is to \"drill down into key dimensions... to uncover root causes or patterns.\n",
        "\n",
        "Which areas in Bangalore are the best for opening a new QSR?"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "tSEEWYTJrWeL"

    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Group data by location\n",
        "location_analysis = df.groupby('location')['rate'].agg(['count', 'mean'])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Identify the top 10 locations by restaurant count\n",
        "top_10_locations = location_analysis.nlargest(10, 'count')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Sort them by mean rating to see which popular area has the best ratings\n",
        "top_10_locations = top_10_locations.sort_values(by='mean', ascending=False)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot the results\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\n",
        "sns.barplot(x=top_10_locations['mean'], y=top_10_locations.index, palette='coolwarm')\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.title('Average Rating in Top 10 Busiest Restaurant Locations')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('Average Rating (out of 5.0)')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Location')\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],

Locations like Bannerghatta Road or Marathahalli, while busy, have lower average ratings, suggesting a more price-sensitive or less-satisfied customer population."

        "from wordcloud import WordCloud\n",
        "\n",
        "# Combine all the cuisine entries into a single string\n",
        "# We'll drop any remaining null values just in case, though our dataset should be clean\n",
        "cuisine_text = ' '.join(df['cuisines'].dropna())\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create the word cloud object\n",
        "wordcloud = WordCloud(width=1000, height=500, background_color='white',\n",
        "                      stopwords=set(['Cafe']),  # We can add common but uninteresting words here\n",
        "                      colormap='autumn').generate(cuisine_text)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Display the generated image\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))\n",
        "plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')\n",
        "plt.axis(\"off\") # Hides the x and y axes\n",
        "plt.title(\"Most Popular Cuisines in Bangalore\")\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "This final phase summarizes the end-to-end exploratory data analysis (EDA) of the Zomato Bangalore restaurant dataset. The objective was to understand the market landscape and identify key success factors to inform the launch of a new food venture.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 1. Data Preparation Summary\n",
        "\n",
        "The raw dataset contained over 51,000 records. A rigorous data preparation phase was conducted to ensure the quality and reliability of the analysis. This involved:\n",
        "* **Cleaning `rate` and `cost_for_two` columns**: Converted these text-based columns into numeric types to enable calculation. Invalid entries like 'NEW' were treated as null values.\n",
        "* **Handling Missing Values**: Rows with missing data in critical analytical columns (`rate`, `cost_for_two`, `location`, `rest_type`, `cuisines`) were removed.\n",
        "* **Final Dataset**: This process resulted in a clean and robust dataset of **41,263 complete records**, which was used for all subsequent analysis.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 2. Key Findings from Exploratory Data Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "### Distribution Analysis\n",
        "* **Restaurant Ratings**: The distribution of ratings is **left-skewed**, with a large concentration of restaurants rated between **3.5 and 4.2**. This indicates a competitive market where customers have high standards. A rating above 4.0 is a clear indicator of a high-performing establishment.\n",
        "* **Cost for Two**: The cost distribution is heavily **right-skewed**, showing that the market is dominated by budget-friendly and mid-range restaurants (under ₹1,000). This suggests that the majority of the customer base is price-sensitive.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Outlier and Relation Analysis\n",
        "* **Outliers**: The analysis revealed that rating outliers are primarily on the low end (below 2.5), highlighting a market intolerance for poor quality. Cost outliers are exclusively on the high end, confirming a small but distinct luxury dining segment.\n",
        "* **Cost vs. Rating**: A scatter plot showed only a **weak positive correlation** between cost and rating. This is a critical insight: **high price does not guarantee a high rating**. Customers recognize and reward quality across all price points.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Comparative and Dimension Analysis\n",
        "* **Restaurant Type Performance**: Experience-focused venues like **Pubs, Microbreweries, and Casual Dining** tend to receive the highest average ratings. The 'Quick Bites' (QSR) model is viable but generally achieves mid-range ratings, implying that a QSR must be exceptional in quality to stand out.\n",
        "* **Top Locations**: A drill-down into the top 10 busiest restaurant locations revealed that **Koramangala and Indiranagar** have the highest average customer ratings. These areas represent \"Tier 1\" locations with a high density of discerning customers who reward quality.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Bonus: Cuisine Analysis\n",
        "* A word cloud of cuisines showed that the market is dominated by **North Indian, Chinese, and South Indian** food. The term **\"Healthy Food\"** was present but significantly less prominent, indicating a less saturated market niche and a potential opportunity.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3. Final Strategic Recommendations\n",
        "\n",
        "Based on the data-driven insights from this analysis, the following strategic recommendations can be made for launching a new food venture in Bangalore:\n",
        "\n",
        "1.  **Target Tier 1 Locations**: Prioritize launching in a high-performing neighborhood like **Koramangala or Indiranagar**. These areas have a proven, large customer base that appreciates and rewards high-quality dining experiences.\n",
        "2.  **Focus on Quality, Not Price**: Success is driven by quality, not a high price point. A **competitive mid-range pricing strategy** is optimal. The primary focus should be on delivering an exceptional product and service, as this is what correlates with top-tier ratings.\n",
        "3.  **Excel Within the Business Model**: If pursuing a QSR model, aim to be a market leader in quality. Since QSRs are not the highest-rated category on average, differentiation through superior food, service, and brand identity is crucial for success.\n",
        "4.  **Leverage the Market Niche**: There is a clear opportunity in the **\"Healthy Food\"** segment. This niche is less saturated than mainstream cuisines, offering a strategic opening for a new brand to establish itself."
      ],

        "id": "9G7cwatXxv8M"
